hands_on_practices.solution:
Start from the equilibrium condition at freeze-out ($dX_n/dt=0$):
$$\lambda'_{p\to n}(1-X_n)=\lambda'_{n\to p}X_n\,. $$

Using the CPT-violated rates,
$$\lambda'_{p\to n}=\lambda_{pn}(1-\delta),\quad 
  \lambda'_{n\to p}=\lambda_{np}(1+\delta),$$
we get
$$\frac{X_n}{1-X_n}
  =\frac{\lambda'_{p\to n}}{\lambda'_{n\to p}}
  =\frac{\lambda_{pn}(1-\delta)}{\lambda_{np}(1+\delta)}\,. $$

By detailed balance in the unperturbed rates,
$$\frac{\lambda_{pn}}{\lambda_{np}}
  =\exp\Bigl(-\frac{Q}{k_B T_f}\Bigr)\,,$$
so at $T=T_f$ the neutron-to-proton ratio freezes to
$$\frac{n_n}{n_p}
  =\frac{X_n}{1-X_n}
  =\exp\Bigl(-\frac{Q}{k_B T_f}\Bigr)\,\frac{1-\delta}{1+\delta}\,. $$
